SIMPLE: stand
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stand
<hw>Stand</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Stood</conjf> <pr>(st⟦oocr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Standing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>standen</ets>; AS. <ets>standan</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>stonda</ets>, <ets>st⟦amac⟧n</ets>, D. <ets>staan</ets>, OS.
<ets>standan</ets>, <ets>st⟦amac⟧n</ets>, OHG. <ets>stantan</ets>,
<ets>st⟦amac⟧n</ets>, G. <ets>stehen</ets>, Icel. <ets>standa</ets>,
Dan. <ets>staae</ets>, Sw. <ets>st⟦aring⟧</ets>, Goth.
<ets>standan</ets>, Russ. <ets>stoiate</ets>, L. <ets>stare</ets>, Gr.
<grk>'ista`nai</grk> to cause to stand, <grk>sth^nai</grk> to stand,
Skr. <ets>sth⟦amac⟧</ets>. ⟦root⟧163. Cf. <er>Assist</er>,
<er>Constant</er>, <er>Contrast</er>, <er>Desist</er>, <er>Destine</er>,
<er>Ecstasy</er>, <er>Exist</er>, <er>Interstice</er>,
<er>Obstacle</er>, <er>Obstinate</er>, <er>Prest</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Rest</er> remainder, <er>Solstice</er>, <er>Stable</er>, <pos>a. &
n.</pos>, <er>Staff</er>, <er>Stage</er>, <er>Stall</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Stamen</er>, <er>Stanchion</er>, <er>Stanza</er>, <er>State</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Statute</er>, <er>Stead</er>, <er>Steed</er>,
<er>Stool</er>, <er>Stud</er> of horses, <er>Substance</er>,
<er>System</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be at rest in an erect
position; to be fixed in an upright or firm position</def>; as:
<sd>(a)</sd> <def>To be supported on the feet, in an erect or nearly
erect position; -- opposed to <contr>lie</contr>, <contr>sit</contr>,
<contr>kneel</contr>, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I pray you all, <xex>stand</xex>
up!⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To continue upright in a
certain locality, as a tree fixed by the roots, or a building resting on
its foundation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>stands</qex> as it were to the ground yglued.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ruined wall⟦br⟧
<qex>Stands</qex> when its wind-worn battlements are gone.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To occupy or hold a place; to have a situation; to
be situated or located; <as>as, Paris <ex>stands</ex> on the
Seine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wite ye not where there <qex>stands</qex> a little town?</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cease from progress; not to proceed; to stop; to
pause; to halt; to remain stationary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I charge thee, <qex>stand</qex>,⟦br⟧
And tell thy name.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The star, which they saw in the east, went before them, till it
came and <qex>stood</qex> over where the young child was.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. ii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To remain without ruin or injury; to hold good
against tendencies to impair or injure; to be permanent; to endure; to
last; hence, to find endurance, strength, or resources.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My mind on its own center <qex>stands</qex> unmoved.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To maintain one's ground; to be acquitted; not to
fail or yield; to be safe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Readers by whose judgment I would <qex>stand</qex> or fall.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To maintain an invincible or permanent attitude; to
be fixed, steady, or firm; to take a position in resistance or
opposition.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>standing</xex> pattern of their
imitation.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king granted the Jews . . . to gather themselves together, and
to <qex>stand</qex> for their life.</q> <rj><qau>Esther viii.
11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To adhere to fixed principles; to maintain moral
rectitude; to keep from falling into error or vice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We must labor so as to <qex>stand</qex> with godliness, according
to his appointment.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To have or maintain a position, order, or rank; to
be in a particular relation; <as>as, Christian charity, or love,
<ex>stands</ex> first in the rank of gifts</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To be in some particular state; to have essence or
being; to be; to consist.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Sacrifices . . . which
<xex>stood</xex> only in meats and drinks.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Heb. ix.
10.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Accomplish what your signs foreshow;⟦br⟧
I <qex>stand</qex> resigned, and am prepared to go.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou seest how it <qex>stands</qex> with me, and that I may not
tarry.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To be consistent; to agree; to accord.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Doubt me not; by heaven, I will do nothing⟦br⟧
But what may <qex>stand</qex> with honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Massinger.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To hold a course at sea; <as>as,
to <ex>stand</ex> from the shore; to <ex>stand</ex> for the
harbor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From the same parts of heaven his navy <qex>stands</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <def>To offer one's self, or to be offered, as a
candidate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>stood</qex> to be elected one of the proctors of the
university.</q> <rj><qau>Walton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>13.</sn> <def>To stagnate; not to flow; to be
motionless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or the black water of Pomptina <qex>stands</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>14.</sn> <def>To measure when erect on the feet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Six feet two, as I think, he <qex>stands</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>15.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To be or remain as it
is; to continue in force; to have efficacy or validity; to abide.</def>
<au>Bouvier.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To appear in court.</def>
<au>Burrill.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>16.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>To be, or signify that
one is, willing to play with one's hand as dealt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stand by</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a preparatory
order, equivalent to <altname>Be ready</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>To
stand against</b></col>, <cd>to oppose; to resist.</cd> -- <col><b>To
stand by</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To be near; to be a spectator; to
be present</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be aside; to be set aside with
disregard</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧In the interim [we] let the commands <xex>stand
by</xex> neglected.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dr. H. More.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
maintain; to defend; to support; not to desert; <as>as, <ex>to stand
by</ex> one's principles or party</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To rest on
for support; to be supported by</cd>. <au>Whitgift.</au> <sd>(e)</sd>
<cd>To remain as a spectator, and take no part in an action; <as>as, we
can't just <ex>stand</ex> idly <ex>by</ex> while people are being
killed</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand corrected</b></col>, <cd>to be set
right, as after an error in a statement of fact; to admit having been in
error.</cd> <au>Wycherley.</au> -- <col><b>To stand fast</b></col>,
<cd>to be fixed; to be unshaken or immovable.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand
firmly on</b></col>, <cd>to be satisfied or convinced of.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧Though Page be a secure fool, and <xex>stands</xex> so
<xex>firmly on</xex> his wife's frailty.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> --
<col><b>To stand for</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To side with; to
espouse the cause of; to support; to maintain, or to profess or attempt
to maintain; to defend.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>stand</xex> wholly
<xex>for</xex> you.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be in the
place of; to be the substitute or representative of; to represent;
<as>as, a cipher at the left hand of a figure <ex>stands for</ex>
nothing</as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I will not trouble myself, whether these names
<xex>stand for</xex> the same thing, or really include one
another.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Locke.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To tolerate; <as>as, I
won't <ex>stand for</ex> any delay</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand
in</b></col>, <cd>to cost.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The same <xex>standeth</xex> them
<xex>in</xex> much less cost.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Robynson (More's
Utopia).</au>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>The Punic wars could not have <qex>stood</qex> the human race
<qex>in</qex> less than three millions of the species.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
-- <col><b>To stand in hand</b></col>, <cd>to conduce to one's interest;
to be serviceable or advantageous.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand
off</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To keep at a distance</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>Not to comply</cd>. <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To keep at a distance in
friendship, social intercourse, or acquaintance</cd>. <sd>(d)</sd>
<cd>To appear prominent; to have relief</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧Picture is best
when it <xex>standeth off</xex>, as if it were carved.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir H.
Wotton.</au> -- <col><b>To stand off and on</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to remain near a coast by sailing toward land
and then from it.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand on</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to continue on the same tack or course.</cd> --
<col><b>To stand out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To project; to be
prominent</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧Their eyes <xex>stand out</xex> with
fatness.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Psalm lxxiii. 7.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To persist in
opposition or resistance; not to yield or comply; not to give way or
recede.</cd>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>His spirit is come in,⟦br⟧
That so <qex>stood out</qex> against the holy church.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
-- <col><b>To stand to</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To ply; to urge; to
persevere in using</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Stand to</xex> your tackles, mates,
and stretch your oars.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Dryden.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
remain fixed in a purpose or opinion.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I will <xex>stand
to</xex> it, that this is his sense.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To abide by; to adhere to; as to a contract, assertion,
promise, etc.; <as>as, <ex>to stand to</ex> an award; <ex>to stand
to</ex> one's word</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>Not to yield; not to fly;
to maintain, as one's ground</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧Their lives and fortunes were
put in safety, whether they <xex>stood to</xex> it or ran away.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Bacon.</au> <sd>(e)</sd> <cd>To be consistent with; to agree with;
<as>as, it <ex>stands to</ex> reason that he could not have done
so</as>; same as <cref>stand with</cref>, below .</cd> <sd>(f)</sd>
<cd>To support; to uphold</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Stand to</xex> me in this
cause.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To stand together</b></col>,
<cd>to be consistent; to agree.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand to
reason</b></col> <cd>to be reasonable; to be expected.</cd> --
<col><b>To stand to sea</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to direct the
course from land.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand under</b></col>, <cd>to
undergo; to withstand.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To stand
up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To rise from sitting; to be on the
feet</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To arise in order to speak or act</cd>.
⟦ldquo⟧Against whom, when the accusers <xex>stood up</xex>, they brought
none accusation of such things as I supposed.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Acts xxv.
18.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To rise and stand on end, as the hair.</cd>
<sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To put one's self in opposition; to contend</cd>.
⟦ldquo⟧Once we <xex>stood up</xex> about the corn.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>
-- <col><b>To stand up for</b></col>, <cd>to defend; to justify; to
support, or attempt to support; <as>as, <ex>to stand up for</ex> the
administration</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand upon</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To concern; to interest</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To
value; to esteem</cd>. ⟦ldquo⟧We highly esteem and <xex>stand</xex> much
<xex>upon</xex> our birth.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Ray.</au> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
insist on; to attach much importance to; <as>as, <ex>to stand upon</ex>
security; <ex>to stand upon</ex> ceremony</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To
attack; to assault.</cd> <mark>[A Hebraism]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧So I
<xex>stood upon</xex> him, and slew him.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>2 Sam. i. 10.</au>
-- <col><b>To stand with</b></col>, <cd>to be consistent with.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧It <xex>stands with</xex> reason that they should be rewarded
liberally.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir J. Davies.</au></cs><-- usu. . -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stand
<hw>Stand</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To endure; to sustain; to bear; <as>as, I can not <ex>stand</ex>
the cold or the heat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To resist, without yielding or receding; to
withstand.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Love <xex>stood</xex> the siege.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>stood</qex> the furious foe.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To abide by; to submit to; to suffer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid him disband his legions, . . . ⟦br⟧
And <qex>stand</qex> the judgment of a Roman senate.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To set upright; to cause to stand; <as>as, to
<ex>stand</ex> a book on the shelf; to <ex>stand</ex> a man on his
feet</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be at the expense of; to pay for; <as>as, to
<ex>stand</ex> a treat</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To stand fire</b></col>, <cd>to receive the fire of arms
from an enemy without giving way.</cd> -- <col><b>To stand one's
ground</b></col>, <cd>to keep the ground or station one has taken; to
maintain one's position.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Peasants and burghers, however
brave, are unable <xex>to stand their ground</xex> against veteran
soldiers.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Macaulay.</au> -- <col><b>To stand trial</b></col>,
<cd>to sustain the trial or examination of a cause; not to give up
without trial.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stand
<hw>Stand</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>stand</ets>. See <er>Stand</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of standing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I took my <qex>stand</qex> upon an eminence . . . to look into
their several ladings.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A halt or stop for the purpose of defense,
resistance, or opposition; <as>as, to come to, or to make, a
<ex>stand</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vice is at <qex>stand</qex>, and at the highest flow.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place or post where one stands; a place where one
may stand while observing or waiting for something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have found you out a <qex>stand</qex> most fit,⟦br⟧
Where you may have such vantage on the duke,⟦br⟧
He shall not pass you.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A station in a city or town where carriages or
wagons stand for hire; <as>as, a cab <ex>stand</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A raised platform or station where a race or other
outdoor spectacle may be viewed; <as>as, the judge's or the grand
<ex>stand</ex> at a race course</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A small table; also, something on or in which
anything may be laid, hung, or placed upright; <as>as, a
hat<ex>stand</ex>; an umbrella <ex>stand</ex>; a music
<ex>stand</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The place where a witness stands to testify in
court.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The situation of a shop, store, hotel, etc.; <as>as,
a good, bad, or convenient <ex>stand</ex> for business</as>.</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>Rank; post; station; standing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Father, since your fortune did attain⟦br⟧
So high a <qex>stand</qex>, I mean not to descend.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>A state of perplexity or embarrassment; <as>as, to
be at a <ex>stand</ex> what to do</as>.</def>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>A young tree, usually reserved when other trees are
cut; also, a tree growing or standing upon its own root, in distinction
from one produced from a scion set in a stock, either of the same or
another kind of tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>12.</sn> <fld>(Com.)</fld> <def>A weight of from two hundred and
fifty to three hundred pounds, -- used in weighing pitch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Microscope stand</b></col>, <cd>the instrument, excepting
the eyepiece, objective, and other removable optical parts.</cd> --
<col><b>Stand of ammunition</b></col>, <cd>the projectile, cartridge,
and sabot connected together.</cd> -- <col><b>Stand of arms</b></col>.
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Arms</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Stand of
colors</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a single color, or flag.</cd>
<au>Wilhelm (Mil. Dict.)</au> -- <col><b>To be at a stand</b></col>,
<cd>to be stationary or motionless; to be at a standstill; hence, to be
perplexed; to be embarrassed.</cd> -- <col><b>To make a stand</b></col>,
<cd>to halt for the purpose of offering resistance to a pursuing
enemy.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Stop; halt; rest; interruption; obstruction;
perplexity; difficulty; embarrassment; hesitation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Standage</ent>⟦br⟧
